Kolnar GreenNugs<br>
49th leaf <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utalanos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Talanos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#333399>(4/4/01 8:19:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovespells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2261.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Maybe not...</span><hr size=1> Don't get too hasty.  You're in the stage of druid life where you find yourself playing the utility backup role alot in group; buffing, parking, backup healing, and tossing off the occasional nuke when mana allows.  Yes, you are about to recieve Superior Heal.  Yes, you will be a better healer after that.  You'll even be able to primary in KC or low impact Seb groups given enchanters and/or bards.  <br>
<br>
However.<br>
<br>
Most of your healing power comes off regen spells.  If you try to constantly keep your primary tank alive with heals, you'll go oom pretty fast.  It's the chrolo/regrowth that's working in conjuction with your heals that make you viable.  And those aren't cast as often, hence the spec check doesn't go into effect as much.  Every alt spell is either low mana (snares, roots), cast periodically and during allowed downtime (buffs), or are out of group spells where saving mana isn't very relevant (tps, sows, etc).  Hence spec: alt is good, but not as efficient at making you a better healer and buffer than spec: evo is at making you a good nuker.<br>
<br>
I was evo until 53, switched to alt when they first gave us superior heal, and have since switched back after finding that druids are much better offensive casters in the endgame than they are healers.  Stick with it, it pays off.<br>
<br>
